We'll set aside 10,000 email messages

62
00:02:22.008 --> 00:02:24.002
for our training set.

63
00:02:24.002 --> 00:02:26.003
We'll use it to build our model.

64
00:02:26.003 --> 00:02:29.005
This training data has 9,000 regular messages,

65
00:02:29.005 --> 00:02:33.000
and 1000 messages labeled as spam.

66
00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:35.003
We'll also set aside a million messages

67
00:02:35.003 --> 00:02:37.000
for our test data.

68
00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:39.004
This test data is unlabeled.

69
00:02:39.004 --> 00:02:41.006
That means that it's unlike our training set,

70
00:02:41.006 --> 00:02:43.005
no one has correctly labeled

71
00:02:43.005 --> 00:02:45.006
any of the messages is spam.

72
00:02:45.006 --> 00:02:46.008
That would be a lot of work

73
00:02:46.008 --> 00:02:48.009
for a million messages.

74
00:02:48.009 --> 00:02:51.000
Your training data is then used

75
00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:54.005
to let the machine identify the spam messages.

76
00:02:54.005 --> 00:02:56.002
Then once the machine learning algorithm

77
00:02:56.002 --> 00:02:57.004
gets close to identifying

78
00:02:57.004 --> 00:02:59.006
the thousand spam messages,

79
00:02:59.006 --> 00:03:03.002
you'll try it on the larger test data set.

80
00:03:03.002 --> 00:03:04.005
Once you're satisfied,

81
00:03:04.005 --> 00:03:08.000
that will be your initial data model.

82
00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:09.006
Now, this machine learning algorithm

83
00:03:09.006 --> 00:03:11.004
only has two options.

84
